Simplify: $$\dfrac{\sqrt{338}}{\sqrt{288}}+\dfrac{\sqrt{150}}{\sqrt{96}}.$$Express your answer as a common fraction.
inference:
$$\dfrac{\sqrt{338}}{\sqrt{288}}+\dfrac{\sqrt{150}}{\sqrt{96}}$$ 
$$=\dfrac{\sqrt{338 \div 2}}{\sqrt{288 \div 12}}+\dfrac{\sqrt{150 \div 6}}{\sqrt{96 \div 12}}$$ 
$$=\dfrac{\sqrt{169}}{\sqrt{144}}+\dfrac{\sqrt{25}}{\sqrt{8}}$$ 
$$=\dfrac{13}{12}+\dfrac{5}{2\sqrt{2}}$$
$$=\dfrac{13}{12}+\dfrac{5\sqrt{2}}{2\sqrt{2} \cdot\sqrt{2}}$$
$$=\dfrac{13}{12}+\dfrac{5\sqrt{2}}{4}$$
$$=\dfrac{13}{12}+\dfrac{15\sqrt{2}}{12}$$
$$=\dfrac{13+15\sqrt{2}}{12}$$

Final Answer: $\boxed{\dfrac{13+15\sqrt{2}}{12}}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: We can simplify each square root first: $\sqrt{338}=\sqrt{2\cdot169}=13\sqrt2$, $\sqrt{288}=\sqrt{2\cdot144}=12\sqrt2$, $\sqrt{150}=\sqrt{6\cdot25}=5\sqrt6$, and $\sqrt{96}=\sqrt{6\cdot16}=4\sqrt6$. Now we can cancel a lot: $$\dfrac{13\sqrt2}{12\sqrt2}+\dfrac{5\sqrt6}{4\sqrt6}=\dfrac{13}{12}+\dfrac54=\dfrac{13+15}{12}=\dfrac{28}{12}=\boxed{\frac{7}{3}}.$$
